{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491636"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:56:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:56:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1004"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1004"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.11,0.23,0.46,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1004"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99151"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1004"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1004"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81544"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1194"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"649"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34001"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99151"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after being kicked in the head by a horse. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears confused. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She has a 5 cm laceration on her scalp. Her speech is understandable but she is not oriented to time, place, or person. Her eyes remain closed when her name is called; however, she opens her eyes in response to pain when the doctor examines her head laceration. She reaches up to push the doctor\u0027s hand away from the painful area.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most accurate Glasgow Coma Scale score?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["8","9","10","11","12"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) is a standardised tool for assessing consciousness level in trauma patients. This patient demonstrates the following responses:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E11\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct total score, calculated as follows: Eye opening to pain (E=2) + Confused conversation (V=4) + Localising to pain (M=5) = 11/15.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E12\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate better neurological function than demonstrated. While the verbal and motor scores are correct (V=4, M=5), this score would require spontaneous eye opening (E=4) which is not present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E10\u003C/strong\u003E would underestimate her level of consciousness. This score might be calculated if the motor response was incorrectly scored as withdrawal (M=4) rather than localising (M=5).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E9\u003C/strong\u003E significantly underestimates her consciousness level. While she is confused, she is able to converse, indicating better function than this score would suggest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E8\u003C/strong\u003E represents the threshold for severe head injury requiring intubation. This patient\u0027s ability to converse, albeit in a confused manner, and localise pain places her well above this level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe GCS is an essential tool in trauma assessment. A total score of 13-15 indicates mild head injury, 9-12 moderate injury, and \u22648 severe injury. Serial GCS measurements are valuable in monitoring neurological deterioration or improvement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) comprises three components: eye opening (E), verbal response (V), and motor response (M).","A confused but conversant patient scores 4 points on the verbal component of GCS.","Localising to pain scores 5 points on the motor component of GCS."],"references":["Reed, D 2011,\u00a0Initial Management of Closed Head Injury in Adults 2nd\u00a0Edition,\u00a0NSW Health."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81544"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1004"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81544"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-19T18:51:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-19T18:52:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1004"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99151"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/